headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: Cingular and Nextwave Sign Deal
summary: Cingular, a leading wireless phone company, has signed an agreement to buy wireless licenses for 34 markets from NextWave Telecom for $1.4 billion, the companies said yesterday. The sale, representing about one-fifth of NextWave's spectrum licenses, is subject to approval by the Federal Communications Commission and the federal bankruptcy court that is overseeing NextWave's reorganization. Other companies have the right to bid a higher price. NextWave will maintain a presence in 20 of the 34 markets. The licenses would give Cingular, a joint venture of BellSouth and SBC, room to grow in some of the most lucrative urban markets, including Atlanta, Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Houston, Los Angeles, San Francisco and Washington. In addition, the deal will give entry into a handful of other markets, including El Paso, Portland, Ore., and Salt Lake City. Executives of NextWave, which owns licenses in 95 of the largest markets nationwide, said the money would be used to pay the debt owed the F.C.C. and to help finance future ventures as it tries to emerge from bankruptcy protection. Jennifer 8. Lee (NYT)

headline: SBC to Offer Wi-Fi Access at 6,000 Spots
summary: SBC Communications is expected to announce today plans to provide wireless Internet access at 6,000 hotels, airports, convention centers, restaurants and other public locations. SBC, which is based in San Antonio, says it will deploy its network over the next three years at locations mostly in its 13-state territory, which includes Texas, California, and Connecticut. Some service will be available by the end of the year, the company said, but SBC has not disclosed how much it will charge users for network access.

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: Cingular Fined $12.1 Million By Regulator
summary: Cingular Wireless has been fined $12.1 million by California's utility regulator after it ruled that the company had provided inadequate service and violated state law. From January 2000 to May 2002, Cingular did not allow new users a grace period to cancel service without paying contract-termination fees as high as $550, the state agency, the California Public Utilities Commission, said in a decision posted on its Web site yesterday. The company also did not tell users about problems with its wireless network in 2001, the decision said. A spokesman for Cingular, a joint venture of SBC Communications and BellSouth based in Atlanta, did not immediately respond to a call for comment. Earlier yesterday, Cingular and 22 other United States cellular companies adopted voluntary customer rights standards, trying to derail tougher rules proposed by the California commission. The commission also ordered Cingular to reimburse customers who paid the contract-termination fee during the period.

headline: Keeping Tabs on Baby And Her Toasty Blanket

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: Supreme Court Rejects W WorldCom Appeal
summary: The United States Supreme Court rejected an appeal yesterday by WorldCom in a dispute with SBC Communications over rules for letting competitors connect into local-phone markets. WorldCom and Wisconsin regulators had sought to reinstate the state's rule for reaching network-connection agreements. A federal appeals court threw out the state rule, saying federal law pre-empted it. The 1996 Telecommunications Act requires the former Bell regional phone companies to open their markets to competition by leasing network components to new competitors. Under the law, leasing plans are reached by negotiation or arbitration and then must be approved by state regulators, with a possible federal court appeal. WorldCom said Wisconsin's procedure would let competitors enter the market sooner.

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: SBC Posts 62% Plunge In Earnings
summary: SBC Communications, the nation's No.2 local telephone company, said yesterday that fourth-quarter earnings dropped 62 percent on shrinking sales of telephone access lines and one-time charges. SBC also said a decline in revenues would stabilize in 2004, but added that its expansion into the large-business services and satellite television markets would weigh on 2004 earnings. headline: F.C.C. Chairman Urges Phone Companies to Settle on Rates
summary: The chairman of the Federal Communications Commission urged the nation's telephone companies yesterday to sit down for 30 days to settle on the appropriate rates for gaining access to local networks. If they cannot agree, the chairman, Michael K. Powell, said he will propose that the commission adopt interim rules for the use of the networks. headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: AT&T Loses Bid On Part-Internet Calls
summary: The Federal Communications Commission rejected AT&T's bid to pay lower fees to local telephone companies for completing calls routed partially over the Internet, a victory for SBC Communications. By a 5-to-0 vote yesterday , the F.C.C. turned down AT&T's October 2002 request. The agency did not decide whether AT&T owes payments it has withheld from local phone carriers while the agency reviewed the matter. Any such claims will be decided on a case-by-case basis, an F.C.C. spokesman, David Fiske, said. The F.C.C. chairman, Michael K. Powell, who has said Internet phone service should be subject to few regulations, decided the AT&T calls are not different enough from conventional circuit-switched phone service. AT&T, trying to pare some of its $10.8 billion in annual access costs, has said the ''arcane'' fees discourage investment in Internet-based technology that benefits consumers.

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: Verizon Rivals Offered Higher Rate-Leasing Plans
summary: Verizon Communications, the telecommunications giant based in New York, introduced a contractual framework yesterday for leasing its lines to competing telephone companies. Verizon said that it would lease its lines in customized three-year deals to competitors. Verizon, which operates in 30 states, said the price would vary by state but would typically range from $20 to $24 per telephone line a month, with the cost rising each subsequent year. The offer from Verizon follows similar proposals by other regional telephone giants, like SBC and BellSouth. Generally, the offers come after a recent appeals court decision that threw out federal rules forcing the dominant local phone companies, like Verizon, to lease their networks to competitors at low rates set by state regulators. Matt Richtel (NYT)

headline: The Spurs Win ... No, Wait, the Lakers Win
summary: With fans standing a few feet away screaming, ''It ain't good, it ain't good,'' three referees and a host of players gathered around a television monitor Thursday night at the SBC Center. One of the greatest finishes in National Basketball Association history, and perhaps the deciding moment in this Western Conference semifinal series, was at stake. For about a minute, the lead official, Danny Crawford, crouched and stared at the replay showing on the monitor. Then, ignoring the Spurs' faithful nearby, he stood and yelled, ''The basket's good,'' giving the Los Angeles Lakers a miraculous 74-73 victory over the San Antonio Spurs.

headline: A Labor Agreement For SBC and Union
summary: SBC Communications and the Communication Workers of America reached a five-year labor agreement last Tuesday, just hours after the union returned from a four-day work stoppage. The deal, which affects 5,500 SBC workers in Connecticut, calls for an average yearly wage increase of 2.5 percent, along with an average annual payment of $300; the maintaining of current health benefits for members and retirees, but with an increase in co-pays and other associated costs; guaranteed employment for current members whose jobs might be eliminated in the future, and access to new jobs for anyone now doing traditional phone work.

headline: The Express Lane to the Internet, Now With Fewer Bumps
summary: LIKE most busy people, Gina Gellerman had better things to do on her Sundays than watch her computer struggle to download Web sites. A preschool teacher in Napa, Calif., Ms. Gellerman wanted to use her days off to catch up on the news, check the entertainment in her town and, most important, plan for her wedding in July. Frustrated with the slow speeds in her dial-up plan with AOL, she asked her friends and family about their high-speed Internet connections. After weighing the merits of broadband sold by cable providers and others, she chose a plan from her telephone company, SBC, which offers a service jointly with Yahoo at $29.95 a month.

headline: Trying to Revive Struggling AT&T: A Job Made, It Seems, for Sisyphus
summary: When he is not trying to rebuild his company, David W. Dorman, the chief executive of AT&T, has been known to go angling for bonefish. The silvery fish swim in full view in shallow water, yet move so fast that a whole day can go by without a bite. When one does take the bait, the fight can last half an hour. Mr. Dorman's experience in the surf is an apt analogy for his day job running the world's best-known telephone company. The problems facing the heir of Ma Bell are obvious to everyone in the industry, yet hard to grasp, let alone fix. And when AT&T finds a solution to one of its many problems, another struggle develops.

headline: Long-Distance Carriers Take A Blow, but It's No Knockout
summary: Phone companies like AT&T, MCI and Sprint, with their long-distance businesses in trouble, suffered a big blow on Wednesday with the Bush administration's decision to side with the regional Bell companies on the issue of local access fees. But that decision is unlikely to cause any immediate consolidation in the industry or damage the long-distance giants as quickly or harshly as they have predicted, industry analysts said. That is because those carriers have been pushing to develop new sources of revenue, the analysts said, and this week's bad news will most likely accelerate those efforts. Legal challenges by the long-distance carriers, state governments and others could also delay any damage.

headline: The White House Hangs Up
summary: The Bush administration is abandoning the landmark 1996 Telecommunications Act, which spawned a new era of competition in telephone service. That is the net effect of its refusal to appeal to the Supreme Court a federal court decision striking down rules that gave local phone companies access to the Baby Bells' networks. Even more disturbing, the administration pressured the Federal Communications Commission, ostensibly an independent agency, to abstain from filing its own appeal in defense of its own rules. The core of the 1996 legislation was a requirement that local phone companies -- the regional Baby Bells, like Verizon and SBC, created with the breakup of Ma Bell a decade earlier -- open up their local markets to competition by leasing access to their lines and other equipment before being allowed to offer long-distance service. The Baby Bells have grudgingly complied, and some 20 million households get their local service from competitors.

headline: The Bells and the Ruling on Access Fees
summary: The decision by the Bush administration last week to side with the regional Bell companies in their legal fight over the access fees they charge others to lease their phone lines has set off alarm bells among consumer groups, long-distance providers and state utility commissions. The groups say that an appeals court decision to remove the cap on these access fees, which goes into effect today, will give the Bells a free hand to raise the prices they charge AT&T, MCI and hundreds of other companies trying to get into the local phone market. It will also push many smaller phone companies out of business, they say, and ultimately lead to higher phone rates for consumers.

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: SBC To Develop New Fiber Optic Lines
summary: SBC Communications said yesterday that it intends to spend $4 billion to $6 billion over the next five years to deploy fiber optic lines capable of delivering next-generation television, Internet and voice services. The company said the deployment would be contingent on whether regulatory rules remain intact that would not force SBC -- and other regional Bell operating companies -- to lease their networks to competitors at low rates set by states. The company said that once the regulatory rules were clarified, it would deploy a network designed to deliver high-definition television, high-speed Internet service, and telephone calls delivered via the Internet through technology known as VOIP. SBC said it was already testing various applications of the network, including working with Microsoft to create digital television services. Matt Richtel (NYT)

headline: Technology Briefing | Telecommunications: SBC And BellSouth Can Buy Back Licenses
summary: SBC Communications Inc. and BellSouth can buy back wireless licenses in California and Indiana that the companies sold four years ago when they secured federal antitrust approval for their Cingular Wireless venture, the Justice Department said yesterday. The announcement is a preliminary step toward antitrust approval of Cingular's planned $41 billion purchase of AT&T Wireless Services. The Justice Department said it had not made a decision on that accord. When they formed Cingular, SBC and BellSouth signed a settlement in which they agreed to sell wireless businesses in California and Indiana markets to AT&T Wireless. Cingular would reacquire those licenses in a takeover of AT&T Wireless. In its announcement yesterday, the Justice Department said the new agreement modified the original settlement so that SBC and BellSouth would not be in violation of the accord once they acquire AT&T Wireless. The Justice Department said new competition in the Indiana and California markets had eliminated the antitrust concerns that prompted the 2000 settlement.

headline: F.C.C. Approves Internet Access On Power Lines
summary: Clearing the way for homes and businesses to receive high-speed Internet services through their electrical outlets, the Federal Communications Commission adopted rules on Thursday that would enable the utility companies to offer an alternative to the broadband communications services now provided by cable and phone companies. As a further spur to the rollout of broadband Internet services, the F.C.C. also ruled that the regional Bell companies do not have to give competitors access to fiber optic lines that reach into consumers' home -- a decision that prompted two of the Bells, SBC Communications and BellSouth, to announce that they would move quickly to build new fiber optic networks in residential neighborhoods. The ruling was criticized by rivals of the Bells and consumer groups, which called it anticompetitive and said it would lead to higher prices.

But he would have appreciated the predicament of the San Francisco Giants and their fans this week, as they waited for Barry Bonds to return to the lineup. Bonds, the seven-time National League most valuable player who is threatening to eclipse Hank Aaron's record for career home runs, played in what the Giants called a simulated game at SBC Park on Thursday afternoon, though it was not much more than a few rounds of batting practice against live pitching. He even sent a fastball from a young right-hander named Kevin Correia into the right-field bleachers. But when the real game against the Chicago Cubs began a few hours later, he was back where he has been all season: on the disabled list.

headline: Some New Wrinkles; Bonds, at 41 Years Old, Nearly Hits a Home Run In His Return to the Giants
summary: After he received his third standing ovation Monday night -- in the bottom of the second inning -- Barry Bonds showed that he was worth the wait. Bonds, the San Francisco Giants' slugger, fouled off five pitches before doubling in his first at-bat since having three operations on his right knee in eight months. The ball left the park in left-center, but only because a fan reached down and deflected it into the stands. The crowd of 39,095 at SBC Park was momentarily delirious as the scoreboard flashed 704. Many thought Bonds, who is third on the major league career home run list with 703, had moved one closer to Babe Ruth's 714 and Hank Aaron's 755.

headline: Bonds and Fans Inspired After Only One At-Bat
summary: The rubber chickens' return to SBC Park on a cold Monday evening warmed the hearts of San Francisco Giants fans. The chickens had been gone for a while, but they were back in celebration of the return of Barry Bonds to the Giants' lineup. The 41-year-old Bonds cracked a double in his first at-bat after missing all season because of three operations on his right knee. The Giants beat the first-place San Diego Padre and Bonds was back in the lineup Tuesday, starting in left field. That means the chickens will probably be out in a flock for the rest of the season. And why not?

headline: Taking Minority-Owned Businesses Under Their Wing
summary: FOUR years ago, Group O Direct, which handles rebates and other fulfillment aspects of customer promotions, was a $4 million-a-year company that barely turned a profit. Michael J. De La Cruz, its vice president for sales and marketing, said that bigotry -- the company is owned by Mexican-Americans -- accounted for some of the problem. But the bigger part was that Group O Direct, though it had been around since 1974, did not know how to navigate corporate shoals. Then, in 2001, SBC Communications, seeking more minority vendors, took Group O Direct, in Milan, Ill., under its wing. ''They led us through their procurement process, what certifications we needed, how to write a bid, who to contact, how to set prices,'' Mr. De La Cruz said. SBC then gave Group O Direct a small contract. A few years later, the Microsoft Corporation helped Group O Direct further ''enhance and refine our business processes,'' as Mr. De La Cruz put it, then gave the company a contract, too. One result is that Group O Direct's revenues will probably exceed $50 million this year.

headline: A Pension Rule, Sometimes Murky, Is Under Pressure
summary: Herb Zydney, who retired as an AT&T executive in 1996, is worried about his pension. Switched into Lucent Technologies' retirement plan during its spinoff from AT&T, he complains that Lucent has invested in ''a bunch of risky stuff,'' in part because of an accounting provision that gives it a financial incentive to do so. Lucent has already been through one wrenching financial crisis, in the early 2000's, and should its pension plan fail, Mr. Zydney would lose a big part of his benefit. ''But I'm almost more concerned as an investor than I am as a retiree,'' added Mr. Zydney, 72, who owns Lucent stock in a self-directed individual retirement account.

headline: Looking Ahead
summary: DIAL M FOR MERGER The Federal Communications Commission could decide as soon as this week whether to approve the proposed $80 billion combination of AT&T and BellSouth. Then again, it could decide not to decide; the deal is on a meeting agenda for Friday, but the F.C.C. has postponed the decision more than once. At issue is whether the commissioners ought to impose any conditions on the deal, and, if so, what they should be. The transaction, which would bring under one corporate roof the dominant telephone companies in California, Texas, the Midwest and much of the South, has been approved by both companies shareholders, state regulators and the Justice Department.
